                  </persName>
            . I was employed to watch the prisoner, and afterwrds took him.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written defece, pleading distress.</p>
               <p>MR. JONES. He left my service while I was in the country, in consequence of which I discharged him; he petitioned to return, and Isaid I would give him 15s. a week tillhe cold get a better place - since that his wages have been raised, in consequence of his family; he broke his thigh in my employ, and I thought I was in duty bound to keep him.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 41.</p>
